In the 2010s, uprisings of the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant | Islamic State]] (IS), formerly called the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL) or the Islamic State of Iraq and Syria (ISIS), have led to violations of religious freedom in certain parts of Iraq. IS is a [[Sunni]] [[jihadism|jihadist]] group that claims religious authority over all [[Muslim]]s across the world<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arabic.cnn.com/middleeast/2014/06/29/urgent-isis-declares-caliphate|title=داعش تعلن تأسيس دولة الخلافة وتسميتها "الدولة الإسلامية" فقط دون العراق والشام والبغدادي أميرها وتحذر "لا عذر لمن يتخلف عن البيعة|publisher=Arabic CNN|date=29 June 2014|accessdate=31 July 2014}}</ref> and aspires to bring most of the Muslim-inhabited regions of the world under its political control beginning with [[Iraq]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Isis rebels declare 'Islamic state' in Iraq and Syria|date=30 June 2014|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-28082962|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=30 June 2014}}</ref> ISIS follows an extreme anti-Western interpretation of Islam, promotes religious violence and regards those who do not agree with its interpretations as infidels or apostates. Concurrently, IS aims to establish a [[Salafi movement|Salafist]]-orientated Islamist state in Iraq, Syria and other parts of the Levant.<ref>{{cite news|title=Islamic State|url=http://www.nationalsecurity.gov.au/Listedterroristorganisations/Pages/IslamicState.aspx|accessdate=22 July 2014|work=Australian National Security|agency=Australian Government}}</ref>

As ISIL loses territory throughout Iraq, the armed forces and allied militias have restored crosses and Christians are being allowed to finally return to their homes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianheadlines.com/blog/christians-return-to-iraq-and-reopen-churches.html|title=Christians Return to Iraq and Reopen Churches|author=|date=|website=christianheadlines.com|accessdate=15 April 2018}}</ref> 

==Status of religious freedom==
===Restrictions on religious freedom===
There were allegations that the [[Kurdistan Regional Government]] (KRG) engaged in discriminatory behavior against Christians. [[Assyrian people|Assyrian]] Christians alleged that the Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) dominated judiciary continued to discriminate routinely against Assyrians and failed to enforce judgments in their favor. The KRG rejects allegations that the Kurdish government ever aimed to discriminate against Christians in any way.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kurdishaspect.com/doc912101.html|title=Kurdishaspect.com|author=|date=|website=www.kurdishaspect.com|accessdate=15 April 2018}}</ref>

