{{short description|Visigothic church near Burgos, Spain}}
[[Image:Santamariadelarafront.jpg|thumb|A view of the surviving west face of the Visigothic church. Initially the centre part of this wall would have been on the interior of the original church.]]
The church of '''Santa María de Lara''', also known as the '''Ermita''' ({{lang-en|[[Hermitage (religious retreat)|hermitage]]}}) de Santa María, is one of the last surviving [[Visigoth]] churches on the [[Iberian Peninsula]],<ref name="rough"/> located near the village of Quintanilla de las Viñas,<ref name="planetware">[http://www.planetware.com/burgos/quintanilla-de-las-vinas-e-castl-quivin.htm Travel Guide Website]</ref> not far from the city of [[Burgos]], in the [[Castile and León]] region in Spain,<ref name="jdie">[http://www.jdiezarnal.com/quintanilla.html An informative website explaining many details concerning the church] {{es icon}}</ref> [[Archeologist]]s have yet to confirm its period of construction but the church has been placed by scholars have placed it between the 7th century, where it is more frequently located, and the 10th century.<ref>{{cite book|last= Utrero Agudo|first=María de los Ángeles|title=Iglesias tardoantiguas y altomedievales en la Península Ibérica: análisis arqueológico y sistemas de abovedamiento|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=457w8IGP8HkC&pg=PA511|date=1 January 2006|publisher= CSIC Press|language=Spanish|isbn=978-84-00-08510-0|pages=511–512|chapter=Quintanilla de las Viñas, Santa María de}}</ref><ref name=Villalon2004>{{cite journal|url= http://revistas.um.es/ayc/article/view/53051/51161 |title=Quintanilla de las Viñas en el contexto del arte altomedieval. |journal=Antigüedad y Cristianismo |first= María Cruz |last=Villalón |year=2004 |accessdate=22 August 2013|issue=XXI|pages=101–135|language=Spanish|issn=1989-6182|format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url= http://dialnet.unirioja.es/descarga/articulo/1006644.pdf |title=Quintanilla de las Viñas y el Arte Cordobés|journal=Norba-Arte |first= María Cruz |last=Villalón |year=2002–2003|accessdate=22 August 2013|volume=XXII-XXIII|pages=341–349|language=Spanish|issn=0213-2214}}</ref> The church is notable not only for its age and [[architecture|architectural]] type, but also because it is believed to contain the earliest representation of [[Christ]] in Spanish [[religious art]].<ref name="rough">''Rough Guide to Spain'' - Simon Baskett, 12th Edition, February 2007, Page 480</ref> It was classified as a [[Monumento nacional (Spain)|national monument]] on November 25, 1929.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.mcu.es/bienes/buscarDetalleBienesInmuebles.do?brscgi_DOCN=000015407&brscgi_BCSID=88a0f945&language=en&prev_layout=bienesInmueblesResultado&layout=bienesInmueblesDetalle |title=Ermita de Nuestra Señora - n°RI-51-0000342|author=Ministerio de Educación, Cultura y Deporte |work=Registro de Bienes de Interés Cultural |year=2013 |accessdate=22 August 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref>

==History==

===Early history===
The geographical area surrounding Santa María De Lara was populated by numerous [[Roman villa]]e preceding the construction of the church.<ref name="smdl"/> After the [[Visigoths]] had invaded the Iberian Peninsula (particularly the area we now know as Spain) and the [[Roman Empire|Romans]] had left the area, they settled in Quintillana de las Vinas, and built the church of Santa María De Lara, around the beginning of the 8th century. Soon afterwards, in 711 AD, the [[Moors]]   invaded the Iberian Peninsula<ref name="brittanica1">''Encyclopædia Britannica'' (Second Edition), 1970, pages 140(b)-141(a)</ref> and Lara was abandoned as the populace fled north to the [[Picos de Europa|mountains]].<ref name="smdl">"Santa María De Lara", An informative booklet on the church - Jesus Vicario Moreno, 1992.</ref>

In the 9th century, during the Spanish [[Reconquista]], the areas that were previously abandoned (such as Lara), were repopulated, although the buildings were largely in ruins. Santa María De Lara was neglected during the period of [[Moors|Moorish]] rule, and therefore the church had to be rebuilt. A funerary [[stela]] that is now housed in the Museum of Burgos that has been studied by archeologists, is believed to record the date of the reconstruction of Santa María De Lara. It is inscribed with the letters '''DCCCC''' (...), and despite the only partial remnant of the date, it is widely believed that this refers to the year 902<ref name="smdl"/> (bearing in mind that the inscription adheres to the Spanish medieval [[Chronological dating|dating system]], from which 38 years must be subtracted to obtain the European chronological year).
[[Image:Santamariadelaraback.jpg|thumb|left|A view of the western side of the church. The ruins of the foundations of the previously sizeable nave can be seen, as well as rooms that provided for the monks who lived in Santa María de Lara during the 10th century. This part of the church collapsed during the period of time that the church was abandoned, from around 1100.]]

A document that has been dated from the year 967 AD (or the Spanish [[Medieval]] date 929) records a monetary donation to the church and the monastery that, at that time, was under the control of Santa María de Lara, by a woman named ''Muniadona'', the mother of [[Fernán González of Castile]].<ref name="smdl"/> However, due to the lack of documents from that early era, historians have been unable to verify the location of this monastery.

In 1038, the church was donated to the nearby monastery of [[San Pedro de Arlanza]]<ref name="jdie"/> and from then on the church began a gradual decline both in religious status and architectural stability. Undated documents from the [[Bishop]]ry of Burgos later refer to it as a 'hermitage'.<ref name="smdl"/>' After that, the church was abandoned, and parts of the building collapsed  and much of its ancient [[Wood carving|carvings]] and decoration was lost.

===Discovery and modern history===
In 1921, a local [[parish priest]], was walking near Quintanilla de las Vinas, when he came across the remains of Santa María de Lara, forgotten since the early [[Middle Ages]] and hidden by thick bush. Don Bonifacio Zamora, the priest, strived to bring his discovery to the interest of historians and experts.<ref name="smdl"/> However, until 1927, he was unsuccessful and the site was used simply as a [[corral]] for livestock. In 1927, the church was finally brought to the attention of experts such as Helmut Schlunk, a notable German scholar, who, amongst others, visited this 'newly discovered' Visigoth church in order to research it.<ref name="smdl"/><ref name="WhitehillClapham2012">{{cite journal|last1=Whitehill|first1=W. M.|last2=Clapham|first2=A. W.|title=The Church of Quintanilla de las Viñas|journal=The Antiquaries Journal|volume=17 |issue=1|year=1937|pages=16–27 |issn=0003-5815|doi=10.1017/S0003581500010581}}</ref><ref name="Porter1928">{{cite book|last=Kingsley Porter|first=Arthur |authorlink=Arthur Kingsley Porter|title=Spanish Romanesque Sculpture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JGbqAAAAMAAJ|year=1928|publisher=Pantheon casa editrice|pages=37–38}}</ref><ref>Schlunk, Helmut, “Arte Visigodo”. in ''Ars Hispaniae'', vol. II. Madrid, 1947.</ref>

After two years of studying the site, it was granted 'National Monument' status on 25 November 1929. Later, during the 1930s, extensive excavations were carried out that revealed a large amount of data that shows the area was inhabited from early times. The research undertaken in the 1920s and 1930s has given us almost all we know about the church today. Many of the [[artifact (archaeology)|artefact]]s uncovered, such as funerary [[stela]]e, [[dolmen]]s and objects from [[Roman villa]]e, are now housed in the 'Museo Provincial de Burgos.<ref name="smdl"/>'

Up until the 1970s, the church could only be reached by a local road, until Jesus Vicario Moreno, who looked after Santa María de Lara and showed it to visitors until his recent death, oversaw the construction of an [[asphalt]] road leading to the church from Quintanilla de las Vinas, where he lived. Tourism and visitors to the site have provided money to keep the church stable and protect it with projects such as the modern wooden roof. Numbers of visitors have increased significantly and in 1992, 8000 tourists were recorded to have visited the site.<ref name="smdl"/>

[[Image:Wisig Quintañilla de las Vigñas plan new.png|thumb|right|250px|A basic plan of the church. The area shaded in blue still stands and is covered by a modern wooden roof. The non-shaded areas are ruined foundations. (Iñiguez, 1955)<ref name="Almech1955">{{cite book|last= Iñiguez Almech|first=Francisco|title=Algunos problemas de las viejas iglesias españolas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bX1ynQEACAAJ|year=1955|publisher=Consejo Superior de Investigaciones Cientificas|language=Spanish|pages=9–180|volume=VII|series=Cuadernos de Trabajos de la Escuela Española de Arqueología de Roma}}</ref>]]

==Connected historic persons==

===Lady Flammola===
Lady Flammola is mentioned in an [[inscription]] carved onto the right side of the [[triumphal arch]] within the church   of the church. Translations differ, but it is believed that the text, reading ''{{lang|la|+ OC EXIGUUM EXIGUA OFF(ERO) D(E)O FLAMMOLA VOTUM}}'', meaning "Flammola, the least of the least, makes this promised offering to God".<ref name=Villalon2004/><ref>{{cite journal |last=Sepúlveda González |first=María de los Ángeles |title=Los anagramas y el programa iconográfico de Quintanilla de las Viñas: una hipótesis de interpretación |journal=En La España Medieval |volume=V |publisher=Editorial de la Universidad Complutense |location=Madrid |year=1986 |url=http://revistas.ucm.es/index.php/ELEM/article/download/ELEM8686221217A/24339 |format=PDF}}</ref> Another translation is: ''This small gift the Lady Flammola offers to God''.<ref name="ema">[http://www.earlymedievalart.com/category/stonework/ A webpage featuring a short article regarding the carvings within the church]</ref> Dona Lambra, as modern historians now refer to Lady Flammola,<ref name="smdl"/> possibly ordered the [[Building restoration|restoration]] of the church in the 10th century, and supported it with the money that she donated according to the inscription.<ref name="smdl"/> However, there are numerous women dating from that period of time that bear the same name, so a more accurate dating of the inscription may reveal precisely who it was that ordered the restoration.

===Fernán González family===
Muniadona features in an early document from 967 AD,<ref name="smdl"/> which records her giving a donation to the church. Muniadona was the mother of Count [[Fernán González of Castile]] (who at that point ruled over Castile<ref>[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/490665/Ramiro-II#ref=ref182291 "Ramiro II"] Online ''Britannica'' article</ref>).

Fernán González of Castile, the first independent count of Castile, was closely linked to the church, which is evident for three reasons. First, he was a member of the influential Lara family, and shares his name with the church.<ref name="fernan">[http://www.biografiasyvidas.com/biografia/f/fernan_gonzalez.htm A short biography of Fernan González] {{es icon}}</ref> He grew up in, and later commanded, the castle of Lara,<ref name="fernan"/> which is visible from Santa María de Lara with favourable weather.<ref name="smdl"/> He was buried in the monastery of [[San Pedro de Arlanza]],<ref name="fernan"/> which at that point owned Santa María de Lara.

